comments.text:
I was obsessed with this case from the start. I found it to be one of the most intriguing unsolved disappearances of all time. A few years after it all happened several investigators and YouTubers really started to dig into the story and many new facts and evidence were brought to the forefront. The most frustrating part of all of the evidence was that so much so it contradicted all of the other evidence. It seemed like there was just as much evidence leaning towards the "lost in jungle" theory as the foul play theory. 

It got to the point where it was impossible to come to any plausible conclusion because you just had no idea who was telling the truth and who was lying or what evidence was genuine or not. I finally stepped away a few years back and put the whole mess behind me. I could only imagine how the girls' parents must have felt going on this emotional roller coaster as they became aware of all the contradicting evidence coming out every few months. 

I just have to say that I'm very grateful to you for all effort you've put into both of your new theory videos. I must admit the numerous grammatical and spelling errors had me a little annoyed at times but the amazing content is where your video shines through. There is a lot of speculating done in the latter half of your video BUT your theory logically fits almost every piece known evidence. That my  friend, is something no other video has ever been able to do. Even the best theory videos are riddled with contradictions. You've done an amazing job examining all of evidence from many different sources and sorting everything out into a very convincing theory. Thank you so much! I have a strong feeling this video will finally help get this mystery solved and bring closure to so many of the girls' family and friends. 

I know I am really late to the party commenting on this video since it came out quite a while ago but I just had to say something.

Why I Think Foul Play Was Involved:

1) Kris' hair appears to look way too good, after 8 long days lost in the jungle.

Spending 8 days in a jungle with lots of rain, dirt, plants, insects, etc. and your hair being that clean 8 days after getting lost in a jungle is just ridiculous. Many speculate that Kris fell and got injured early on in their disappearance, you mean to tell me she fell and her hair was completely untouched? no twigs, dirt, nothing? okay. I'm sorry but personally my hair would look completely messed up after 1 night being lost in a jungle, never mind 8.

Some say that Kris' might of washed her hair, I just really doubt that.

First, you think her dirty hair would really be a concern for her, being lost for days in a foreign jungle far far from home?

Second, they had no hair products on them. Washing hair with just river water would leave it looking frizzy, not like the hair that looks like on photos from April 1st.

2) Before going to the Pianista trail, locals have said that they saw the girls being approached by an off road vehicle.

Please be aware that I am not accusing any of these people specifically of harming the girls, as that would be not fair without more evidence.

After the girls had a short conversation with the locals, they were approached by tour guide Feliciano's off road vehicle. Son of Feliciano, Henry Gonzalez, was driving that vehicle. He was accompanied by his friend Jose Manuel Murgas.

Henry offered the girls a ride to the Pianista trail, which was only 5 minutes away from that point.

The girls accepted the ride and got to the Pianista trail to begin their hike, alone. So those boys had the information that the girls were alone.

Now like I said, this doesn't mean that it was them specifically that did something to the girls, but they had the information that they were alone. Whether or not they passed on this information to other third parties, we don't know.

This is still some crucial information.

3) That same off road vehicle picked up the girls after they returned

This was witnessed by 2 locals.

One of these locals was the taxi driver - Leonardo Arturo Gonzalez.

Leonardo apparently knew more than he publicly stated about what he witnessed.

Leonardo later was found drowned, on March 3rd 2015. Just before the case was closed.

My theory is that Leonardo was killed because he knew something that the killers didn't want him to. To prevent him from spilling this information to unwanted sources, the killers took his life.

The girls were witnessed heading to the road by locals between 2:30pm - 3:30pm, 5 hours after their start time.

This time is consistent with the time it actually takes to hike the Pianista trail, and return back from the hike.

The witness stated that the girls looked like they already walked a good amount, so it is possible that he saw them after their returned from their hike.

Now to the main point, the same off road vehicle that drove the girls to the hike, picked them up from the hike. There were 3 guys in the car: Henry Gonzalez, Jose Manuel Murgas, and Osman Valenzuela.

A popular theory is that they headed to Caldera Hot Springs, to relax after a long day of hiking. Seems logical to me.

4) Panamanian authorities botched this case from the very beginning.

A Dutch journalist mentioned the unprofessionalism by the Panamanian authorities to investigate the case at a criminal level.

This is a snippet from a video featuring what he said:

"For too long they considered a possible accident, or a possible case of them getting lost. And all that time they didn't invest in a proper criminal investigation. Therefore, very crucial time has been lost. Within hours, at the last days but ideally sooner, you need to interview all witnesses, in a very intensive and thorough manner. You need to do technical research very early on and investigate telephone data."

It is no secret that the Panamanian authorities neglected this case from the very beginning, how can you be this careless and irresponsible?

The families of the girls filed a lawsuit against the Panamanian authorities for the mishandling of the evidence.

Were they trying to cover something up?

A motive for covering the truth could be that they wanted to paint the picture that the girls were lost in order to protect their tourism reputation. That is what I personally believe.

5) Tampering of camera / SD card.

Most here already know about image 509 here, so I won't go in too much detail about that.

But image 509, the photo between last day photo and first night photo, was safe deleted.

Safe deleting requires a special computer software.

If the image was just simply deleted from the camera, a professional would still be able to retrieve this image using a computer. That was not the case.

The Dutch authorities themselves came to a conclusion that the camera and SD card were tampered with, so this is no secret.

In my opinion, image 509 was something that the Panamanian authorities absolutely did not want anyone to see. And this doesn't have to mean that 509 showed the girls injured/dead or showed their murderers or anything like that, but it could have simply been a picture that was not on the trail or near the jungle. In order to depict their narrative of the girls being "lost in a jungle", the Panamanian authorities destroyed this image.

extensive research, thanks for the great video and the alternate hypothesis. i'm of the mind that this was foul play as well... however, this video right here is of a man who documented the whole trail after the summit for us to see: channel "Romain C" part 2... at the 24:00 mark of that video you can see that picture 508 of Kris by the stream shows her continuing on toward the Serpent trail, and not back toward the summit as the expert local had said... not saying you are wrong with your theory, but Kris is NOT heading back in the direction from where they came in this photo. That being said, it does seem like a good place to turn around if you're hiking on this trail. a sudden change in scenery from the enclosed walls of rock and thick shrubbery from where they came.

edit: it's worth mentioning in 508 you can see Kris facing back across the stream, and behind her seems to be an incline of the trail leading up. if you watch the video, you'll see this is an illusion, as what appears to be a path behind her is not part of the trail. instead, the path continues much more horizontally to the right of her as she faces the camera.

As the trail continues past the stream, there are several places that "could" potentially cause one to get lost, but i wouldn't say it's likely. There are several forks that veer off, and appear as though they could be part of the trail if you were an unexperienced hiker and weren't paying attention. while i don't think they are pronounced enough to cause any real confusion, if you were to veer off the trail in those surroundings, it would be easy to lose your bearings. Sad story, I guess we'll never know for sure now but it is still more likely they went and got lost, got hurt and perished in the elements.  But there are so many irrelevant points brought up that have no significance, presented as crucial pieces of evidence. eg;
-Who was or wasn't wearing a backpack in which photo - over 4 hours, it's just as likely they just swapped from time to time along the way as they got tired - it doesn't mean anything and has no relation to which direction they were walking in.
-Why would they stop twice in the same spot to waste storage space to take the same posed selfie pictures in the same place after they've already done it going one way?  A normal person just keeps walking home.  The photos were taken at the same time, in one session.
-The highly dramatic travel channel documentary took the word of one indigenous man that they were not actually photographed at the Serpentine trail and took it as true gospel over all the other professionals who actually walked the trail searching for them specifically using their camera trail.  He was simply wrong.  That was not a photo of them heading back up the trail home, it was confirmed to be them having passed the "do not pass" sign and continuing down on into the deep jungle.  They may well have paid that native chap to say what they wanted him to say.  They even posed at a random stream crossing claiming it proved the girls were going back up the trail home, even though the rock formations were completely different.  They BS'ed that it was different because "it's a dynamic setting".  Those large boulders were completely embedded and had been there for likely thousands of years.  No small stream or even raging river will move them, they are fixed and will only be eroded incrementally over hundred of thousands of years.
-It's claimed often there is no way to get lost on this trail. This is preposterous and even Indigenous inhabitants have died on this trail. After the initial tourist trail half where they stopped to take photos, the trail becomes wild and is for the Indigenous people to use, it is genuinely wild and small with multiple possible tracks becoming available.
-Speculation about the other people is fine, but people seem to get fixated on the ideas taught to them that these countries are always drug gang murder capitals of the world.  Panama is one of the safest countries in the Americas and that town particularly, even safer.  There is the occasional serious crime like there is in any town but this was shocking for them too.  There is still no evidence that any of those people were there or involved in any way - small town gossip is real and eyewitness accounts of old memories are proven to be virtually no better than guessing.
